# STRATEGICLAND — Interaction System

> Interactions are **acknowledgments**, not performances.
> The cursor is the audience's hand reaching into the film.
> Every interaction must feel **tactile, weighted, and slightly under-eager**.

---

## 1. Interaction Philosophy

- The default state of the interface is **silent**. Interactions are events, not garnishes.
- Hover states are **acknowledgment**, not transformation. The element should not become a different element.
- Click feedback is felt, not seen — micro-shifts under 6px, never bounces.
- Cursor is the **camera lens**: contextual, intelligent, almost invisible.
- "Magnetic" effects are **gravitational**, never **springy**. Inertia, not elasticity.

---

## 2. Hover Behavior

### 2.1 Allowed hover changes
| Property | Range / Token                | Notes                          |
|----------|------------------------------|--------------------------------|
| `opacity`  | 1 → 0.7 (text), 1 → 0.85 (image) | Default link hover     |
| `color`    | text-primary → text-accent       | Only for links / CTAs   |
| `transform: translateY` | 0 → -2px to -4px      | Only for editorial CTAs |
| `letter-spacing` | base → +0.005em            | Display CTAs only      |
| `filter: brightness` | 1 → 1.04                | Image hover             |

All hover transitions: `EASE.settle`, `DUR.micro` (180ms).

### 2.2 Forbidden hover changes
- ❌ `scale(1.05+)` on UI elements (overgrown).
- ❌ `box-shadow` appearing on hover.
- ❌ Background color flips (fills, accent backgrounds).
- ❌ Border appearance/disappearance.
- ❌ Icon rotations or "playful" micro-animations.
- ❌ `text-decoration: underline` toggling — use a separate animated underline (see §3).

### 2.3 Hover affordance density
- Maximum **1 hover affordance per scene** in editorial chapters.
- Maximum **3 hover affordances per scene** in case study chapters.
- Hover affordances must be **visually identifiable without hovering** — they are not surprises.

---

## 3. Animated Link Underlines

The project uses a custom underline pattern instead of CSS `text-decoration`:

```css
.link {
  position: relative;
  display: inline-block;
}
.link::after {
  content: "";
  position: absolute;
  left: 0; right: 0; bottom: -2px;
  height: 1px;
  background: currentColor;
  transform: scaleX(0);
  transform-origin: right center;
  transition: transform 380ms cubic-bezier(0.16, 1, 0.3, 1);
}
.link:hover::after,
.link:focus-visible::after {
  transform: scaleX(1);
  transform-origin: left center;
}
```

### Constraints
- Underline thickness: always **1px** (display links may use 2px).
- Color: always `currentColor`.
- Origin reverse on out (right) vs in (left) creates the cinematic "wipe" feel.

---

## 4. Cursor System

The site replaces the system cursor with a **custom contextual cursor** on pointer devices.

### 4.1 Default cursor
- A **single 8px circle**, color `--cursor-tone` (defaults to `text-primary` at 0.7 opacity).
- Mix-blend-mode: `difference` (so it remains legible across all backgrounds).
- Position is **lerped** to mouse position with damping factor 0.18 — slight lag = cinematic weight.

### 4.2 Contextual states
The cursor adapts via a context (`<CursorProvider>`) responding to hover targets:

| Target type           | Cursor adaptation                                                |
|-----------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Link / CTA            | Scale to 32px, label appears: `→ visit`                          |
| Image (case study)    | Scale to 64px, label: `view`                                     |
| Draggable / horizontal scroll | Scale to 48px, label: `drag`                             |
| Sound toggle          | Scale to 24px, label: `sound · on/off`                           |
| Disabled              | Cursor disappears (radius → 0) for 200ms, then returns           |

### 4.3 Constraints
- Cursor adapts only **on hover of declared targets** (via `data-cursor="..."` attribute or `useCursor("link")` hook).
- All state transitions: `EASE.settle`, `DUR.quick` (380ms).
- Cursor is **disabled on touch devices** entirely (no pointer = no custom cursor).
- Cursor **must not** ever leave a trail (no particles, no echo, no shadow).

### 4.4 Implementation
```tsx
<CursorProvider>
  {children}
  <CustomCursor />   {/* lives at root, fixed position */}
</CursorProvider>

// In a target
<a data-cursor="link" data-cursor-label="visit">…</a>
```

The cursor reads `data-cursor` attributes via pointer-event delegation (single global listener on body).

